\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Robustness (left) and susceptibility (right) for base, insecure, and secure variants of the four model families. Within each group, bars are ordered left to right as secure (light, \texttt  {////}), base (solid), and insecure (dark, \texttt  {\textbackslash \textbackslash \textbackslash \textbackslash }). Error bars denote standard errors. Insecure variants uniformly cluster in a narrow low-robustness band ($R \approx 2.5$--$4.7$) regardless of their base model's robustness, and all show elevated susceptibility. Secure fine-tuning also reduces robustness, though less severely. For reference, the 17 non-misaligned models benchmarked by \citet  {costa2025moral} span $R \in [3.2, 122.2]$ and $S \in [0.61, 0.96]$.}}{7}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:bars}{{2}{7}{Robustness (left) and susceptibility (right) for base, insecure, and secure variants of the four model families. Within each group, bars are ordered left to right as secure (light, \texttt {////}), base (solid), and insecure (dark, \texttt {\textbackslash \textbackslash \textbackslash \textbackslash }). Error bars denote standard errors. Insecure variants uniformly cluster in a narrow low-robustness band ($R \approx 2.5$--$4.7$) regardless of their base model's robustness, and all show elevated susceptibility. Secure fine-tuning also reduces robustness, though less severely. For reference, the 17 non-misaligned models benchmarked by \citet {costa2025moral} span $R \in [3.2, 122.2]$ and $S \in [0.61, 0.96]$}{figure.2}{}}
